func nextPrime() int {
    for i := 2; i < 1000; i++ {
        if isPrime(i) {
            return i;
        }
    }
    return -1; // no prime found
}

func isPrime(n int) bool {
    for i := 2; i < n; i++ {
        if n%i == 0 {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}

This API uses trial division to check if a number is prime. It iterates from 2 to the square root of the number being tested, checking if it has any divisors other than 1 and itself. If no divisors are found, the number is prime.

The `nextPrime()` function repeatedly iterates over the range of numbers from 2 to 1000, checking if any of them are prime. If a prime is found, it returns that number. If no prime is found, it returns -1.

This API is very brief, as it only contains two functions and has a minimalist design. However, it may not be the most efficient or practical implementation, as it only checks up to 1000 and does not take advantage of any prime number properties or optimizations.

